{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489155"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:06:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:06:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"603"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/603"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.06,0.6,0.02,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"603"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31520"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/603"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"603"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17309"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"474"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2658"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"},{"type":"tags","id":"6623"},{"type":"tags","id":"9876"},{"type":"tags","id":"11539"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"985"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1069"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4842"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/31520"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after falling down the stairs, which he attributes to his legs feeling weak and collapsing under his weight. He did not lose consciousness or hit his head. He has a medical history of peripheral vascular disease and dyslipidaemia, for which he takes atorvastatin 20mg. Physical examination reveals a blood pressure of 160/100 mmHg and a left-sided renal bruit but is otherwise unremarkable. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial blood tests reveal a potassium level of 2.5mmol/L while imaging is unremarkable. An aldosterone/renin ratio is performed and shows a raised plasma renin activity and a raised plasma aldosterone concentration, resulting in a ratio of 8 (normal).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conn syndrome","Addison disease","Renal artery stenosis","Cushing syndrome","Phaeochromocytoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA raised plasma renin activity and raised plasma aldosterone concentration with an aldosterone/renin ratio of 8 suggests secondary aldosteronism, which would explain the hypokalaemia. This man\u0027s history of peripheral vascular disease with a left-sided renal bruit on examination makes \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal artery stenosis \u003C/strong\u003Ethe most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERenal artery stenosis is most commonly caused by atherosclerotic disease or fibromuscular dysplasia. Decreased renal blood flow results in the release of plasma renin and activation of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system. It is an important cause of secondary hypertension which should be considered with new-onset hypertension (age \u0026lt;30 or \u0026gt;55); malignant, accelerated or resistant hypertension; unexplained renal dysfunction; or history of atherosclerotic vascular disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvasive angiography is the gold standard for the diagnosis of renal artery stenosis, while duplex ultrasonography is an excellent screening test in high-risk patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial treatment should be focused on blood pressure control, treatment of heart failure, reduction of risk factors and prevention of nephropathy. Surgical revascularisation with balloon angioplasty or stent placement in the renal arteries may also be considered in severe cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConn syndrome (primary aldosteronism) should be considered in a patient with hypertension and hypokalaemia. However, the aldosterone/renin ratio is not high enough to support this diagnosis (it is generally \u0026gt;20). Addison disease, or primary adrenal insufficiency, would cause hypotension, not hypertension. Cushing syndrome is characterised by excess plasma cortisol, which can also activate mineralocorticoid receptors on the collecting ducts of the nephron. This would result in negative feedback on the plasma aldosterone concentration and cause a low plasma renin activity and low aldosterone concentration. Phaeochromocytoma is a catecholamine-producing adrenal tumour which results in hypertension. It does not cause hypokalaemia and does not change the plasma renin activity or plasma aldosterone concentration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Possible underlying secondary causes must always be considered in the assessment of patients presenting with hypertension."],"references":["Colyer WR, Eltahawy E, Cooper CJ. Renal artery stenosis: optimizing diagnosis and treatment. Prog Cardiovasc Dis. 2011;54(1):29-35.","Manaktala R, Tafur-Soto JD, White CJ. Renal Artery Stenosis in the Patient with Hypertension: Prevalence, Impact and Management. Integr Blood Press Control. 2020;13:71-82."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17309"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"603"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/17309"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-01-11T16:34:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-01-11T16:34